text: @zaph0id @pmddomingos @dhrtha "Progress in AI is hindered by the lack of a programming language with all the requisite features. Libraries like PyTorch and TensorFlow provide automatic differentiation and efficient GPU implementation, but are additions to Python, which was never intended for AI. Their lack of support for automated reasoning and knowledge acquisition has led to a long and costly series of hacky attempts to tack them on. On the other hand, AI languages like LISP and Prolog lack scalability and support for learning. This paper proposes tensor logic, a language that solves these problems by unifying neural and symbolic AI at a fundamental level. The sole construct in tensor logic is the tensor equation, based on the observation that logical rules and Einstein summation are essentially the same operation, and all else can be reduced to them. I show how to elegantly implement key forms of neural, symbolic and statistical AI in tensor logic, including transformers, formal reasoning, kernel machines and graphical models. Most importantly, tensor logic makes new directions possible, such as sound reasoning in embedding space. This combines the scalability and learnability of neural networks with the reliability and transparency of symbolic reasoning, and is potentially a basis for the wider adoption of AI."

The Principles First, Before the Language
Many of you know how to code in Python, JavaScript, or PHP yet understand almost nothing about programming itself.

These are often the same people who mock Computer Science students for spending time on “useless theories” and “irrelevant concepts.” But  those very theories and concepts are what make CS grads stand out  and why companies still rush to hire them.

Because if you can grasp the principles, understand the abstractions, and internalize the concepts, the practical side becomes second nature.
So go back to the foundation. Learn the things that actually matter:

Flowcharts and system design: They may look trivial, but they’re gold when you start designing scalable systems.

Algorithms: Learn how they work, how to design them, and why they matter for performance.

Language Translators: Understand compilers, interpreters, and how high-level code becomes machine instructions.

Data Structures: The real building blocks of efficiency and problem-solving.

Computer Architecture: CPUs, memory, threads, caching everything that happens under the hood when your code runs.
The list goes on...
Master the foundations, and you’ll notice how much easier it becomes to learn any new language, even with AI-powered coding tools. You’ll prompt them better, debug faster, and build smarter  because your understanding will come from first principles, not just syntax.

Even LLMs themselves are products of deep theoretical foundations built on mathematics, computer science, and decades of algorithmic research. And the best prompt engineers 
They’re not the ones who just “use” AI.
They’re the ones who understand what they’re prompting for.
